00:18:27.579 --> 00:18:32.699
Okay, so oops, wrong button.

00:18:32.699 --> 00:18:33.699
All right.

00:18:33.699 --> 00:18:34.699
All right.

00:18:34.699 --> 00:18:37.699
So testing in 2023.

00:18:37.739 --> 00:18:43.780
Testing costs, just so you're aware, if it's 45 minutes per testing run, 15 different combinations,

00:18:43.780 --> 00:18:51.900
five days a week, 52 weeks a year, that's over 3,000 CI hours a year for fees and pricing.

00:18:51.900 --> 00:18:54.140
Open source, it's free, which is awesome.

00:18:54.140 --> 00:19:00.099
If you're doing it in private repos, if Shiny Core CI was to be purely private, it'd be

00:19:00.099 --> 00:19:01.619
about 3,000 a month.

00:19:01.619 --> 00:19:04.979
So not crazy, not terrible, but it is expensive.

00:19:04.979 --> 00:19:07.459
But 75% of that cost is for MacOS.

00:19:08.219 --> 00:19:11.099
So if you actually just did Ubuntu testing, it'd be like $300 a month.

00:19:11.099 --> 00:19:17.219
And I think that is very reasonable for the amount of hours that is being executed.

00:19:17.219 --> 00:19:22.260
And release time now, because bugs are being found when they come in, is less than two

00:19:22.260 --> 00:19:24.060
days with four developers.

00:19:24.060 --> 00:19:28.420
And this is because we need to go around to different integrations like Workbench, Shiny

00:19:28.420 --> 00:19:36.020
AppsIO, Shiny Server Open Source or Pro, which aren't there anymore, Workbench, Kinect, IDE.

00:19:36.020 --> 00:19:37.540
So we have to manually go do those.

00:19:37.540 --> 00:19:38.540
We can't get around that.

00:19:38.540 --> 00:19:41.459
And I think two days for four developers is not bad.

00:19:41.459 --> 00:19:44.739
It's probably not even four developers.

00:19:44.739 --> 00:19:47.300
But it does add a cost of weekly maintenance.

00:19:47.300 --> 00:19:52.619
But the confidence is through the roof when we release, because we know the bugs have

00:19:52.619 --> 00:19:56.859
been fixed as they've come in.

00:19:56.859 --> 00:19:57.900
So lessons learned.

00:19:57.900 --> 00:20:00.979
See if I can get this here in about five minutes.

00:20:00.979 --> 00:20:05.819
Number one, minimize the number of screenshot expectations.

00:20:05.819 --> 00:20:09.500
Like the office, GitHub will tell you, hey, I need you to find the difference between

00:20:09.500 --> 00:20:10.500
these two images.

00:20:10.500 --> 00:20:13.979
They look the same, but they're not.

00:20:13.979 --> 00:20:15.859
So I'm actually going to play this game with you.

00:20:15.859 --> 00:20:17.859
I will give you five seconds.

00:20:17.859 --> 00:20:18.859
Spot the difference.

00:20:18.859 --> 00:20:23.859
One, two, three, four, five.

00:20:23.859 --> 00:20:24.859
Awesome.

00:20:24.859 --> 00:20:27.780
Did you find the difference?

00:20:27.780 --> 00:20:31.579
This is this little white space right here.

00:20:31.579 --> 00:20:34.979
That little white space causes a diff to look like this.

00:20:34.979 --> 00:20:38.339
So these images are different, and they are truly different.

00:20:38.339 --> 00:20:42.099
But what happens a lot is extra little things.

00:20:42.099 --> 00:20:47.180
These two images, in a much more favorable comparison, can you spot the difference?

00:20:47.180 --> 00:20:49.180
I'll give you five.

00:20:49.180 --> 00:20:54.219
One, two, three, four, five.

00:20:54.219 --> 00:20:59.219
Just like in the office, Intel said there's seven differences.

00:20:59.219 --> 00:21:00.739
Differences are actually highlighted in red.

00:21:00.739 --> 00:21:03.180
And these are not really differences.

00:21:03.180 --> 00:21:08.619
They're more mistakes from the slider library or issues from there.

00:21:08.619 --> 00:21:10.579
So screenshots are hard.

00:21:10.579 --> 00:21:15.939
Try to minimize them, because little things like this will come up.

00:21:15.939 --> 00:21:20.020
Lesson two, a failure may not be your fault.

00:21:20.020 --> 00:21:27.420
And similar to the slider one, so yeah, I know it's not my fault.

00:21:27.420 --> 00:21:29.699
But it's still my problem.

00:21:29.699 --> 00:21:32.180
And this is because the red dots will show up everywhere.

00:21:32.180 --> 00:21:33.979
We'll have failure messages everywhere.

00:21:33.979 --> 00:21:39.819
Get constant emails from GitHub Actions that, hey, your testing failed.

00:21:39.819 --> 00:21:44.339
But this is because things like GitHub Actions routinely updates their CI machines.

00:21:44.339 --> 00:21:48.219
And slow machines make client-side timing difficult, like if you have CSS animations

00:21:48.300 --> 00:21:53.339
with moving bars or modals or things like that.

00:21:53.339 --> 00:21:57.459
And then there's also lots of trouble with Ubuntu updating their system fonts.

00:21:57.459 --> 00:22:02.020
I know I've talked about this with ShinyTest2, but let's see if you can spot

00:22:02.020 --> 00:22:03.020
the difference on this one.

00:22:03.020 --> 00:22:06.500
I'm actually going to just switch slides and have the images overlaid.

00:22:06.500 --> 00:22:11.819
All right, so here's baseline and new, baseline and new, baseline and new.

00:22:11.819 --> 00:22:15.380
There's not much of a difference, but you can actually see that the baseline has

00:22:15.380 --> 00:22:21.219
like a boldish font in Alabama, and then the new has like a thinner font.

00:22:21.219 --> 00:22:24.500
So the font weight was reduced, and that was a system change.

00:22:24.500 --> 00:22:28.540
Like, can't fix it.

00:22:28.540 --> 00:22:30.339
Test failure, test opportunity.

00:22:30.339 --> 00:22:33.140
Nah, that's test failure.

00:22:33.140 --> 00:22:37.380
So a recommendation is to actually use threshold.

00:22:37.380 --> 00:22:41.699
This will allow for minor differences when comparing screenshots

00:22:41.699 --> 00:22:43.459
within ShinyTest2.

00:22:43.459 --> 00:22:47.540
So in this code here, in the expect screenshot with ShinyTest2,

00:22:47.540 --> 00:22:51.500
just say threshold is like two or something less than five.

00:22:51.500 --> 00:22:56.380
If it was zero, then we would say the images have to be exact same.

00:22:56.380 --> 00:23:00.699
In the case of the modal dialogue, we are doing this because rounded corners

00:23:00.699 --> 00:23:03.339
were being different because they were rounding to the left or to the right

00:23:03.339 --> 00:23:09.140
sometimes, and so we just wanted to make sure that they were not throwing failures

00:23:09.140 --> 00:23:11.140
when comparing the images.

00:23:11.140 --> 00:23:15.500
Please check out the docs in ShinyTest2 Compare Screenshot Threshold.

00:23:15.500 --> 00:23:20.739
This will help you see what values you need to use or even what methods you can

00:23:20.739 --> 00:23:27.459
use to expose how different those images are.

00:23:27.459 --> 00:23:31.140
Lesson three, test values that you can control.

00:23:31.140 --> 00:23:35.579
Yeah, Kaylee has totally said this in the movie.

00:23:35.579 --> 00:23:37.459
So test those values that you can control.

00:23:37.459 --> 00:23:43.739
So if there are dependency changes, you know, they will produce new output values

00:23:43.739 --> 00:23:44.939
like in Plotly.

00:23:44.939 --> 00:23:50.380
So Plotly will change, you know, its internals, and that's not your fault.

00:23:50.380 --> 00:23:54.900
And so really what you should be doing is possibly testing the dataset that's going

00:23:54.900 --> 00:23:57.619
into Plotly and assuming the plot will work.

00:23:57.619 --> 00:24:01.500
So use ShinyExportTestValues to expose those dataset values

00:24:01.500 --> 00:24:03.099
from your server side.

00:24:03.099 --> 00:24:05.500
They won't be exposed anywhere else except in testing mode,

00:24:05.540 --> 00:24:10.380
so you're safe to expose possibly dangerous things.

00:24:10.380 --> 00:24:15.619
And then also, you can do snapshot excluding on your outputs, or you can pre-process your

00:24:15.619 --> 00:24:19.619
input or output, and I'll show you a quick demo of a pre-process your output,

00:24:19.619 --> 00:24:20.939
snapshot output.

00:24:20.939 --> 00:24:25.260
And this is, the snapshot is the JSON values that are saved to disk when you call

00:24:25.260 --> 00:24:28.380
expect values within ShinyTest2.

00:24:28.380 --> 00:24:33.339
So running out of time, so that's why I'm kind of rushing here.

00:24:33.339 --> 00:24:38.339
So in a Plotly example from ShinyTest2 internals testing, we actually,

00:24:38.339 --> 00:24:44.020
this is adjusted for the demonstration, but what we do is normally you'd say

00:24:44.020 --> 00:24:48.699
output my plot, and you'd have Plotly, render Plotly, and you do your plot.

00:24:48.699 --> 00:24:50.420
Great.

00:24:50.420 --> 00:24:55.339
But we can then pipe this into a Shiny snapshot pre-process output,

00:24:55.339 --> 00:24:59.260
and what it'll do is it will provide that JSON object.

00:24:59.260 --> 00:25:01.140
So we're going to parse that JSON.

00:25:01.140 --> 00:25:06.420
We're only going to pull out the X data, the first data, and only the X and Y columns,

00:25:06.420 --> 00:25:12.619
and hopefully, we can get back the cars1 and cars2 for our X and Y data.

00:25:12.619 --> 00:25:17.020
And this way, it allows Plotly to do whatever it wants internally,

00:25:17.020 --> 00:25:18.420
and we're not testing against it.

00:25:18.420 --> 00:25:25.099
So it can hold, it can make changes freely without breaking our tests.

00:25:25.099 --> 00:25:28.979
And finally, lesson four, routine maintenance is maintainable.

00:25:28.979 --> 00:25:33.380
I know this is a little bit of, like, tautology, but if you don't do routine

00:25:33.380 --> 00:25:37.819
maintenance, you might make a PR so big that GitHub won't let you merge it

00:25:37.819 --> 00:25:41.459
because you can't view the website.

00:25:41.459 --> 00:25:44.140
It finally rendered about 15 minutes later.

00:25:44.140 --> 00:25:45.900
It was a lot of fun to get that in.

00:25:49.380 --> 00:25:50.140
Yeah.

00:25:50.140 --> 00:25:51.660
So lessons learned.

00:25:51.660 --> 00:25:55.020
Minimize your screenshots, the count of them.

00:25:55.020 --> 00:25:58.739
Just because it failed doesn't mean it's your fault, but it's still your problem.

00:25:58.739 --> 00:26:03.619
And test values that you can control and perform routine test maintenance to keep

00:26:03.619 --> 00:26:06.780
on top of it.

